Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-02-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Not quite clear on the concept of 'Consistency' in Dialign..
Input.posts:
Hello, In the course, Prof. Provart talks about 'sets of diagonals' being consistent. - Can a single diagonal be consistent ? Consistent with what and in relation to what ? Thanks for clearing this up for me ! Ken :)
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Yes a single diagonal can be consistent. Basically any diagonal that is in the correct orientation (bottom left to top right) is consistent. Any others are in a contrary orientation.
Instructor's post : Yes a single diagonal can be consistent. Basically any diagonal that is in the correct orientation (bottom left to top right) is consistent. Any others are in a contrary orientation.
Upvotes:
0

Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-02-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
Hi,\xA0 Let's say i would like to allign protein sequences \xA0of the same familiy of genes.\xA0which approach would be the most correct? I would say that a global alignment might be the right one because the sequences are closely related (am i wrong?) but at the same time in the same family we could have protein sharing of course similar functions (they are in the same family indeed) but having very different lenghts, so probably also a local allignement hilighting local motifs and patterns among sequences of different lenghts could be appropriate. I don't know if a managed to make my point. Probably in this case MAFFT with a kind of an ibrid approach could be the answer? Thanks
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Emanuele! I think global alignments are more useful when you are trying to see overall similarity across a set of sequences. Local alignments may be more useful when looking for regional or domain-to-domain similarity. Also, when you align globally you are making the assumption that the sequences are similar. If your proteins are closely related, global alignment is probably a good strategy. Local alignments may also allow you to see conserved motifs that may be of functional importance across the family. If the proteins have only recently diverged, local alignments may not be very informative however.
Instructor's post : Hi Emanuele! I think global alignments are more useful when you are trying to see overall similarity across a set of sequences. Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
I am confused about the evolutionary history of the 8 sequences shown on page 1 of the lecture notes. In the video Dr. Provart states that 'the top 4 sequences are more similar in terms of their alignment than the bottom 4 sequences, which are also aligned in the sense that there is an insertion in the 2nd set of 4 sequences down here. So these (the bottom 4) are likely more closely evolutionarily related than these (top) 4 sequences and this can tell us the evolutionary history of a set of sequences that have been aligned.' Can you explain why this is? I would think that closer sequence alignment would indicate closer evolutionary history among the sequences.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
I think what is meant here is that the bottom 4 sequences are closely evolutionarily related to each other, and the top 4 sequences are closely related evolutionarily to each other. This is due to the fact that they align in a more similar manner to each other.

Input.posts:
I'm getting lost during the explanation of how pseudo-replicates are constructed, slide 28, 21:50 '...where you can see that we´ve sampled the first column once, the second column three times...' When looking at these columns, I am not sure what one sampling, or two etc should actually look like. As well, what defines the max number of samples you would take for any column?
Upvotes:
5
Same problem
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Bootstrapping is a way of assigning confidence to a tree. Pseudoreplicates are created through an iterative resampling process. If you have a dataset (set of sequences in this case) of n sequences with m sites (bases or nucleotides), a number of resampled datasets are produced, and each site is sampled at random a number of times. These resampled datasets are used to produce a number of trees which are then all reconciled in order to produce one tree with confidence/bootstrap scores included. Generally, a good number of bootstraps is 500 - 1000 (depending on the time and computing power and size of dataset). A link that may help explain this further is: http://www.icp.ucl.ac.be/~opperd/private/bootstrap.html Hope this helps explain the concept further!

David, I suppose a real hard-core cladist would support using MP over ML since they would claim that it makes the fewest assumptions (explicitly assuming that change is rare and the tree with the smallest number of changes is the best tree). Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
Any clear advantage in using ml vs parsimony? Would there be a situation where parsimony would be better?
Upvotes:
0
Thanks for the reference at the end of lab 4. S Guidon and O Gascuel (2003) A simple, fast, and accurate algorithm to estimate large phylogenies by maximum likelihood. Syst. Biol. 52: 696-704. \xA0
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
David, I suppose a real hard-core cladist would support using MP over ML since they would claim that it makes the fewest assumptions (explicitly assuming that change is rare and the tree with the smallest number of changes is the best tree). Then again, this of course is a major assumption that may or may not hold. As I stressed in the lecture, g enerally, you should try multiple approaches and look for congruence! Best, Nick
